06703nam a22008895i 9783110984309DE-B159720230103011142.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230103t20222023gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831109843097 a10.1515/97831109843092doi  a(DE-B1597)632909  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE04aThe Reception of Ancient Cyprus in Western Culture /ced. by Stella Alekou, Stephen J. Harrison, Spyridon Tzounakas. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2022] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (VIII, 314 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTrends in Classics - Supplementary Volumes ,x1868-4785 ;v13900tFrontmatter -- tPreface and Acknowledgements -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPart I: Cyprus in Latin Literature -- tCyprus and its Myths on the Roman Stage -- tVenus on Cyprus: Interlinked Lists of Aphrodite’s Cypriot Sanctuaries in Latin Poetry -- tIdalion, Satrachus and the Annales of Volusius: The Reception of Cyprus in the Carmina Catulli -- tNil desperandum …. cras ingens iterabimus aequor (Hor. Carm. 1.7): The Foundation of Salamis by a Bastard Archer as an Exemplum in Latin Literature -- tBalance and Excess in Ovid’s Pygmalion Story -- tWas Cyprus Special? The Case of Two Latin Poets -- tInfamem nimio calore Cypron: Ancient Epigrams on Flacci in Cyprus -- tThe Digression on Cyprus in Claudian’s Epithalamium de nuptiis Honorii et Mariae -- tPart II: Cyprus after Antiquity -- tVenus and Adonis from Enheduanna to Shakespeare: The Significance of Ovid’s Cypriot Metamorphoses -- tPilgrims, Merchants and Lovers: The Island of Cyprus in Boccaccio’s Decameron (via Ovid’s Metamorphoses) -- tVenus of Paphos in the Latin Poetry of the Quattrocento -- tOvid’s ‘Good’ Women: The Cypriot Exemplum Against the Background of the Statue (R)evolution -- tOsmosis between High Genres: Ovid’s Tragic Formation of Myrrha’s Tale (Met. 10.298–502) and its Reception in Alfieri’s Homonymous Tragedy -- tTravel, Classical Traditions and Empire: Western Travellers to Cyprus in the Eighteenth and Nineteenth Centuries -- tList of Contributors -- tGeneral Index -- tIndex Locorum0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe reception of ancient Cyprus in the Western world has not received much attention in scholarship, despite the fact that significant literary and extra-literary evidence presented by European intellectuals and artists explicitly or implicitly refers to the history of Cyprus, as well as to the myths and art produced on it or inspired by its landscape. This is a neglect that this volume wishes to address, by re-establishing the literary thread of the representation of ancient Cyprus beyond generic, spatial and temporal limits, and by thus shedding light on its depiction throughout the centuries, from the ancient Roman to the Western world up until modern times. The volume’s central thesis is that a number of Cypriot traditions constitute a unique example of intercultural and multi-level fusions of diverse European civilizations. By investigating the various and often contradictory ways in which Cyprus was represented in Latin literature and beyond, the volume treats its multifaceted reception as a vastly complex matter, and suggests that even though the island has always been an outlier, it has often been explored in literature as an intellectual landscape and a precious pathway between at times conflictual yet compatible worlds.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 4aAntikes Zypern. 4aEuropäische Rezeption. 4aLatein. 4aMythologie.  aAncient Cypriot identity.  aCypriot mythology.  aEuropean reception of Cyprus.  aLatin literature.1 aAlekou, Stella, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlekou, Stel